maximum distance with the current array\n            max_distance = max(max_distance, abs(current_max - min_val), abs(max_val - current_min))\n            \n            # Update the global minimum and maximum values\n            min_val = min(min_val, current_min)\n            max_val = max(max_val, current_max)\n        \n        return max_distance\n```\n\nThis solution efficiently calculates the maximum distance by keeping track of the minimum and maximum values encountered so far and comparing them with the current array's minimum and maximum values. This approach ensures that we only need to traverse the list of arrays once, resulting in a time complexity of O(m), where m is the number of arrays.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}